    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1974-01-28T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1974-01-28T00:00:00-05:00" n="99"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d99">
                <head>99. Memorandum From the President’s Deputy Assistant for National Security
                    Affairs (<persName corresp="#p_SB_1">Scowcroft</persName>) to the President’s
                    Assistant for National Security Affairs (<persName corresp="#p_KHA_1"
                        >Kissinger</persName>)<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d99fn1">
                        <p>Summary: <persName corresp="#p_SB_1">Scowcroft</persName> relayed a query
                            from Secretary of the Treasury <persName corresp="#p_SG_1"
                                >Shultz</persName> to <persName corresp="#p_KHA_1"
                                >Kissinger</persName> regarding a request from <persName
                                corresp="#p_NH_1">Hisham Nazir</persName> that labor economist and
                            Director of the Cost of Living Council <persName corresp="#p_DJT_1">John
                                T. Dunlop</persName> meet with him in Saudi Arabia.</p>
                        <p>Source: National Archives, Nixon Presidential Materials, <gloss
                                target="#t_NSC_1">NSC</gloss> Files, <persName corresp="#p_KHA_1"
                                >Kissinger</persName> Office Files, Box 139, Country Files, Middle
                            East, Saudi Arabia (1). Confidential. <persName corresp="#p_KHA_1"
                                >Kissinger</persName> wrote next to the “Let him go” option: “Only
                            after embargo is lifted can we consider trip. Nazer should be so
                            informed.”</p>
                    </note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1974-01-28">January 28, 1974</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_SG_1">George Shultz</persName> said that Hisham Nazer,
                    head of the Saudi Planning Organization and running the oil organization in
                        <persName corresp="#p_YAZ_1">Yamani</persName>’s absence, has requested that
                        <persName corresp="#p_DJT_1">John Dunlop</persName> come over to meet with
                    him. He knows <persName corresp="#p_DJT_1">Dunlop</persName> well from <persName
                        corresp="#p_DJT_1">Dunlop</persName>’s meetings with him on planning,
                    especially human resource planning, before <persName corresp="#p_DJT_1"
                        >Dunlop</persName> entered the Government. He is requested to come sometime
                    in early March, and <persName corresp="#p_DJT_1">Dunlop</persName> assumes he
                    wishes to talk about economic planning in general and probably what to do with
                    all the oil money.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_SG_1">Shultz</persName> requests your views. I think there
                    are problems with him going, especially prior to the lifting of the embargo and
                    the restoration of production. After that is accomplished, I don’t see any
                    particular difficulty.</p>
                <p>Let him go __________</p>
                <p>No trip __________</p>
                <p>Hold off for now __________</p>
            </div>
